Linux System Information & Monitoring Commands

df -T or lsblk -f or blkid â†’ Show file system types which are mounted

1 Byte = 8 bits
1 KB = 1024 Bytes
1 MB = 1024 KB
1 GB = 1024 MB
1 TB = 1024 GB
1 PB = 1024 TB PB means PetaByte
1 EB = 1024 PB EB means ExaByte
1 ZB = 1024 EB ZB means ZettaByte
1 YB = 1024 ZB YB means YottaByte

Mnemonic to remember the order of units:
Big Kangaroos Make Great Tiny Puppies Eat Zebras Yearly.


| Shortcut  | Action                                       |
| --------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| Ctrl + A  | Move cursor to beginning of line             |
| Ctrl + E  | Move cursor to end of line                   |
| Ctrl + B  | Move cursor back one character               |
| Ctrl + F  | Move cursor forward one character            |
| Alt + B   | Move cursor back one word                    |
| Alt + F   | Move cursor forward one word                 |
| Ctrl + K  | Delete from cursor to end of line            |
| Ctrl + U  | Delete from cursor to beginning of line      |
| Ctrl + W  | Delete word before cursor                    |
| Alt + D   | Delete word after cursor                     |
| Ctrl + Y  | Paste last deleted text                      |
| Ctrl + L  | Clear screen (same as `clear`)               |
| Ctrl + T  | Swap characters before and under cursor      |
| Ctrl + _  | Undo last editing action                     |

uname - Display System Information
    uname -s â†’ Show kernel name
	uname -a â†’ Shows all system information
	uname -r â†’ Displays the kernel release version
	uname -s â†’ Prints the operating system name or kernel name
	uname -m â†’ Displays the machine hardware name/architecture
	uname -n â†’ Shows the hostname
	uname -o â†’ Displays the operating system name
	uname -v â†’ Shows the kernel version
	uname -p â†’ Displays the processor type
	uname -i â†’ Displays the hardware platform

uptime - Check System Uptime
	uptime -p â†’ Pretty format â€“ Shows uptime in a human-readable format (e.g., "up 3 hours, 15 minutes")
	uptime -s â†’ Since format â€“ Displays the system start time (e.g., "2024-04-01 08:30:00")
	uptime -V â†’ Version â€“ Shows the version of the uptime command

Display CPU Information
	nproc â†’ Show the number of processing units available
	nproc --all â†’ Show all processing units, including offline ones

hostname - Display and Set Hostname
hostnamectl â†’ Show system hostname and related information

Modify Hostname:
sudo hostnamectl set-hostname --static new-hostname  
--static -> Set the static hostname for permanent use
--transient -> Set the transient hostname for temporary use
--pretty -> Set the pretty hostname for display purposes
Make it permanent by editing /etc/hostname and /etc/hosts.

Useful Options:
	hostname -s â†’ Short hostname (without domain)
	hostname -f â†’ Fully qualified domain name (FQDN)
	hostname -I â†’ IP address(es)
	hostname -d â†’ DNS Domain name
	hostname -A â†’ All known hostnames

System Reboot History
    last reboot â†’ History of system reboots 
    last -x | grep reboot â†’ Show all reboots 
    last -x | grep shutdown â†’ Show all shutdowns
    last -x | grep runlevel â†’ Show all runlevel changes 
	Runlevel means the state of the system
	0 â†’ Halt, 1 â†’ Single-user mode, 2 â†’ Multi-user mode, 3 â†’ Full multi-user mode, 4 â†’ Unused, 5 â†’ Graphical mode, 6 â†’ Reboot
	last -x | grep runlevel | awk '{print $5,$6,$7,$8}' | date -f - +"%Y-%m-%d %I:%M:%S %p" 
    last -x | grep shutdown | awk '{print $5,$6,$7,$8}' | date -f - +"%Y-%m-%d %I:%M:%S %p" 
    â†’ Show shutdown times in a readable format

Check Primary System IP Address:
hostname -I | awk '{print $1}'

Network Commands
	ip addr â†’ Show IP addresses and network interfaces
	ifconfig â†’ (Deprecated) Display network configuration
    ip addr show dev eth0 â†’ Show IP address for a specific interface`
    ip link show â†’ Show all network interfaces & MAC on the local system
    ip neigh show â†’ Show ARP cache which show MAC address on the network
	ARP means Address Resolution Protocol it is used to find the MAC address of a host
    ip link set eth0 up â†’ Bring up a specific interface
    ip link set eth0 down â†’ Bring down a specific interface

date - Display and Format Date/Time
Show Time with Milliseconds:
date +"%H:%M:%S:%3N"
date +"%I:%M:%S:%3N"
date -f - means "read date strings from the input piped to me"
date -f input.txt -> Read from text file
date -d "2024-04-03 10:15:00" +"%Y-%m-%d %I:%M:%S %p"
Eg : last reboot | awk '{print $5,$6,$7,$8}' | date -f - +"%Y-%m-%d %I:%M:%S %p"

date +%s -> Show current epoch time
Epoch time is the number of seconds that have elapsed since the Unix epoch, which is defined as 00:00:00 UTC on 1 January 1970.
It is commonly used in computing and programming to represent time in a standardized format.

date -d "2024-04-03 10:15:00" +%s
Convert Epoch Time to Normal time:
date -d @1745209628 --> Mon Apr 21 09:57:08 AM IST 2025

Common Formatting Flags:
Flag	Description	Example
%Y	Year (4-digit)	2025
%y	Year (2-digit)	25
%m	Month (01-12)	04
%B	Full month name	April
%b	Abbreviated month name	Apr
%d	Day of month (01-31)	03
%A	Full weekday name	Thursday
%a	Abbreviated weekday name	Thu
%H	Hour (00-23)	14
%I	Hour (01-12)	02
%M	Minutes (00-59)	30
%S	Seconds (00-59)	45
%p	AM/PM	PM
%Z	Time zone	UTC

sudo timedatectl set-timezone Asia/Kolkata -> Set timezone
timedatectl list-timezones â†’ List all time zones
timedatectl set-ntp true â†’ Enable NTP synchronization
timedatectl set-ntp false â†’ Disable NTP synchronization
timedatectl show-timesync â†’ Show NTP synchronization status
timedatectl set-time "2024-04-03 10:15:00" â†’ Set system time

