File Operations
	ls -lh --block-size=1G â†’ Show sizes in GB(Giga Bytes)
	ls -Sl â†’ Sort files by size
	ls -lt â†’ List files by modification time
	ls -lt --block-size=1G â†’ List files by modification time in GB
	ls -lt --block-size=1G | grep -E "pattern1|pattern2" | sort -u â†’ Unique matches
	ls -lt --time-style=long-iso â†’ Show time in long ISO format
	ls -lt --time-style="+%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S:%3N" â†’ Custom time format
	
	cp -u source.txt destination.txt â†’ Copy only if source is newer
	mv -u source.txt destination.txt â†’ Move only if source is newer
	mv -i source.txt destination.txt â†’ Prompt before overwriting
	mv -n source.txt destination.txt â†’ No overwrite if destination exists source.txt
	cp -n source.txt destination.txt â†’ No overwrite if destination exists source.txt
	cp -u source.txt destination.txt â†’ Copy only if source is newer


View File Contents
	cat -n filename â†’ Show with line numbers
	cat -b filename â†’ Ignore blank lines in numbering
	more f1 f2 f3 â†’ View multiple files sequentially
	cat file1 >> file2 â†’ Append file1 to file2
	cat file1 | tee file2 file3 â†’ Copy content to multiple files
	cat file1 | tee -a file2 file3 â†’ Append content to multiple files
	mkdir -p folder{2..7} && for i in folder{2..7}; do cp -r folder1/ "$i"/; done
	cmp file1 file2 â†’ Byte-by-byte file comparison
	vimdiff -O f1 f2 f3 â†’ Open in vertical splits
	diff file1 file2 â†’ Show file differences
	diff -y file1 file2 â†’ Show differences side by side
	
SEARCH COMMANDS
    Syntax : find [path] [options] [expression]

	find . -maxdepth 2 -type d -name "folder*" â†’ Find directories named "folder*" up to 2 levels deep
	find . -type f -iname "test*" -exec cp -t ../folder2/ {} + â†’ Copy all files matching "test*" to folder2
	find . -type f -perm 777 â†’ Files with full permissions
	find . -perm /u=w â†’ Files where the user has write permission
	find . -perm /g=x â†’ Files where the group has execute permission
	find . -perm /o=r â†’ Files where others have read permission
	find . -perm /a=rw â†’ Files where all users have read and write permissions
	find . -type f -empty â†’ Empty files
	find / -user username â†’ Files owned by a specific user
	find / -group groupname â†’ Files belonging to a specific group
	find . -mtime 10 â†’ Modified exactly 10 days ago
	find . -mtime +10 â†’ Modified more than 10 days ago
	find . -mtime -10 â†’ Modified within the last 10 days
		+10 -> More than 10 days ago
		-10 -> Less than 10 days ago 
		 10 -> Exactly 10 days ago
	find . -newer file1 â†’ Files modified after file1
	find . -newer file1 -not -newer file2 â†’ Files modified between file1 and file2
	find . -newermt "2024-01-01 12:00" â†’ Modified after the given date/time
	find . -atime 10 â†’ Accessed exactly 10 days ago
	find . -ctime 10 â†’ Changed status exactly 10 days ago
	find . -cmin -60 â†’ Status changed within the last 60 minutes
	find . -mmin -60 â†’ Modified within the last 60 minutes
	find . -amin -60 â†’ Accessed within the last 60 minutes
	find / -size +50M -size -100M â†’ Files between 50MB and 100MB
	find . -type f -name "*.txt" -exec grep -l "pattern" {} + â†’ Find files containing "pattern"
	find . -type f -name "*.txt" -exec grep -L "pattern" {} + â†’ Find files not containing "pattern"
	find . -type f -newermt "10 days ago" ! -newermt "5 days ago" â†’ Modified between 10 and 5 days ago
	find . -type f -newerct "$(date -d '60 seconds ago')" â†’ Status changed in the last 60 seconds
	find . -name "*.log" | xargs -I {} mv {} archive/ -I {} -> Inserting {} in the command
	xargs -n 1 -> Process one argument at a time
	find . -name "*.txt" | xargs grep "search_string"
	find . -type f -newerct "$(date -d '1 hour ago')" ! -newerct "$(date -d '30 minutes ago')" â†’ Status changed between 1 hour and 30 minutes ago
	stat -c FORMAT file â†’ Custom file info output
    test -d "target" && echo "yes" || echo "no" --> To test directory is there in the path
	test -f "file1.txt" && echo "yes" || echo "no"

stat Format Options
Option	Description
%n	    File name
%s	    File size in bytes
%x	    Access time (atime)
%y	    Modification time (mtime)
%z	    Change time (ctime)
%A	    File permissions(-rw-r--r--)
%U	    Owner name
%G	    Group name
%F	    File type
%a      File permissions(644, 755)
%h	    Number of hard links
%l	    Symbolic link target

grep Commands
	grep "word" file1 file2 file3
	grep -c "word" file
	grep -e "pattern1" -e "pattern2" filename
	grep -L "pattern" filename -> Find files not containing "pattern"
	grep -l "pattern" filename -> Find files containing "pattern"
	grep -v "pattern" filename -> Exclude lines with "pattern"
	grep -i "pattern" filename -> Case-insensitive search
	grep -r "pattern" /path/to/dir -> Recursive search in directory
	grep -w "word" filename -> Match whole word
	grep -n "pattern" filename -> Show line numbers
	grep -A 3 "pattern" filename -> Show 3 lines after the match
	grep -B 3 "pattern" filename -> Show 3 lines before the match
	grep -C 3 "pattern" filename -> Show 3 lines before and after the match
	grep -q "pattern" filename -> Quiet mode (no output, just exit status). Used in scripts
	grep -m 5 "pattern" filename -> Stop after 5 matches
	grep -E "regex" filename -> Extended regex
	grep -F "fixed string" filename -> Fixed string search (faster) 
	Eg grep -F "a.*b" file.txt 
	Finds lines containing the *literal string "a.b" (not regex) â€” no special meaning to * or .
	grep -o "pattern" filename -> Show only matching parts
	grep -r "pattern" /path/to/dir --include="*.txt" -> Search only in .txt files
	grep -r "pattern" /path/to/dir --exclude="*.log" -> Exclude .log files
	grep -r "pattern" /path/to/dir --exclude-dir="dir_name" -> Exclude specific directory
	sudo cut -d: -f1,7 /etc/passwd --> It will show the first and seventh fields of the /etc/passwd file, separated by a colon (:).
	awk NF filename (or) grep -v '^$' filename (or) sed '/^$/d' filename --> It will show the non-blank lines
	sed -i '/^$/d' filename --> To remove blank lines from a file 
	grep -m3 "pattern" filename --> Outputs those first 3 matching lines
	grep -c -a "search_term" possibly_binary.file --> -a is used to treat binary files as text
    
	eval means executes the string as a command
	command ls means executes the command without using shell features like aliases
	type command_name â†’ Show command type (alias, function, built-in, executable)
	which command_name â†’ Show command path

	Default path for user commands is /usr/bin:/bin:/usr/sbin:/sbin used by the shell to search for executable files.
	User path is set in /etc/profile or ~/.bashrc or ~/.bash_profile
	Default path is best to use in scripts to ensure commands are found correctly.

	
	Escape means make special/invisible characters visible
	Literal means treat special characters as normal characters
	\ is the escape character in most shells
	printf "%q\n" * --> %q in printf escapes special characters in a shell-compatible way
	                  (so the output can be reused as input in shell commands).
					--> Guarantees the output is safe for eval or shell reuse.
					--> %q means quote the argument in a way that it can be reused as a shell command.
	Example : 
	121.002.20000#2025+10obj.cfg
	121.002.20000#2025+services\[print\].cfg
	hardlink_file
 
    pom.xml :
	<dependency>
		<groupId>org.example</groupId>
  		<artifactId>my-library</artifactId>
  		<version>8.6.2</version>
	</dependency>

	grep -Po '<artifactId>\K[^<]+' pom.xml # Output : my-library
	  --> -o: Output only the matched part of the line
	  --> \K: A PCRE-specific feature that resets the start of the reported match. So everything matched before \K is excluded from the output.
      --> [^<]+: Matches one or more characters that are not <. This effectively extracts the content inside the <artifactId> tags.
	
	grep -Po '(?<=<artifactId>)[^<]+' pom.xml # Output: 8.6.2
	(?<=pattern)	Positive lookbehind (must be preceded by pattern)
      --> Extract text preceded by <artifactId> tag

	grep -Po '[^<]+(?=</version>)' pom.xml  # Output: version>8.6.2
	(?=pattern)	Positive lookahead (must be followed by pattern)
	   --> Extract text before <version> tag

    tee -a file.txt << 'EOF'
	This is a multi-line input
	EOF

	cat > file.txt << 'EOF'
	This is a multi-line input
	EOF

	sudo only applies to the command you run, not the shell's redirection 
	So, sudo cat > file.txt will not work as expected.

	sudo tee file.txt << 'EOF'
	This is a multi-line input
	EOF 

User Management Commands
	useradd <username> â†’ Just add user without any options
	useradd -m -d /custom/path/yaswanth -s /bin/bash -u 1501 -g users -G sudo,developers -e 2025-12-31 username
	useradd -m username â†’ Create home directory
	useradd -u 1501 username â†’ Assign specific UID
	useradd -g users username â†’ Assign primary group
	useradd -G sudo,developers username â†’ Assign secondary groups
	useradd -s /bin/bash username â†’ Dont Assign shell
	useradd -e YYYY-MM-DD username â†’ Set account expiration date
	useradd -d /custom/path/yaswanth username â†’ Assign custom home directory
	useradd -c "New User" ->Set the default comment (usually full name).
	useradd -s /bin/false username â†’ Disabling the ability to log in for that user.
	for service accounts or users that should not log in interactively but may still be needed for other system tasks 
	(like running background processes or owning files).

	useradd -r username â†’ Add system user (no home directory)
	useradd -N username â†’ No user group

	adduser <username> â†’ Interactive user add
	useradd -U username â†’ User group with same name
	useradd -M username â†’ No home directory (e.g., for system users)

	useradd -D â†’ View default useradd options
	useradd -D -b /opt/users -s /bin/bash  -f 30 -g users username
	# Set default options for new users
	-b â†’ base home directory
	-e â†’ expire date (YYYY-MM-DD)
	-s â†’ default shell (Eg: /etc/skel)	
	-k â†’ skeleton directory
	-f â†’ inactivity period (Eg : 30 days after password expiry it will be disabled)
	-g â†’ default group (Eg : users) 

	userdel username --> Delete user
	userdel -r username --> Delete user and home directory
	userdel -f username --> Delete user even if logged in
	userdel -r -f username --> Force delete user and home directory
	cat /etc/passwd -> Show user details
	cat /etc/shadow -> Show password details

	sudo vipw #Safer way to edit /etc/passwd using the vipw command (locks the file during edit)

	sudo vipw -s username # Edit /etc/shadow safely
	sudo vigr -s group   # Edit /etc/gshadow safely
	cat /etc/environment -> Show environment variables (EDITOR=vim, then source /etc/environment)
	sudo chsh -s /bin/bash jenkins 
	#Interactive and user-friendly, it will also check if the shell exists in /etc/shells and refuse invalid shells.
	chsh = Change SHell 

User mod Command :
sudo usermod -l johnny -u 1600 -d /home/johnny -m -g staff -G docker -s /bin/zsh -e "2023-02-09"  john
What it does:
    -l johnny: Renames user john to johnny
    -u 1600: Changes UID
    -d /home/johnny: Sets new home directory
    -m: Moves home directory contents
    -g staff: Changes primary group
    -G docker: Sets new secondary group
    -s /bin/zsh: Changes login shell

Group Management
	groupadd groupname -> Add group(default GID)
	groupadd -f developers â†’ Don't error if already exists
    groupadd -g 2025 groupname â†’ Add group with specific GID
	addgroup groupname â†’ Add group (Debian/Ubuntu)
	groupadd -r groupname â†’ Add system group
	groupadd -f -r groupname â†’ Add system group if not exists
	usermod -aG groupname username â†’ Add user to group
	deluser username groupname -> Remove user from group (Debian/Ubuntu)
    gpasswd -d username groupname â†’ Remove user from group (Red Hat/CentOS)
	groupmod -n newgroup oldgroup â†’ Rename group
	groupdel groupname â†’ Delete group 
	delgroup groupname -> To remove a group (Debian/Ubuntu only)
	newgrp qa_team  # if your user was recently added to a group and you want to activate the new group membership
	                 ignored without logging out and back in.

Check Group Membership
	id username â†’ Show user ID and groups
	id -g username â†’ Show primary group ID
	id -gn username â†’ Show primary group name
	id -u username â†’ Show user ID
	groups username â†’ Show groups for a user
	getent group groupname â†’ Show group details
	getent passwd username â†’ Show user details

Add all users from groupA to groupB
for i in $(getent group groupA |awk -F: '{print $4}' | tr ',' ' '); do usermod -a -G  groupB "$i";done
Remove all users who are in groupA from groupB     
for i in $(getent group groupA |awk -F: '{print $4}' | tr ',' ' '); do gpasswd -d "$i" groupB;done


ðŸ” chage â€“ User Account Aging & Expiry
Command	                             		 Description
chage -l username	            	List password aging info
chage -E YYYY-MM-DD username		Set account expiration date
usermod -e YYYY-MM-DD username		Set account expiry (alternate method)
chage -W 7 username	            	Warning days before password expires
chage -I 3 username					Inactivate after 3 days of password expiry
chage -d YYYY-MM-DD username		Set last password change date
chage -m MIN_DAYS username			Set minimum days before password change
chage -M MAX_DAYS username			Set maximum days before password expiry
chage -E -1 usname or usermod -e "" username â†’ Remove expiry date

Options:
	-d, --lastday LAST_DAY â†’ Last password change date
	-E, --expiredate EXPIRE_DATE â†’ Expiration date (YYYY-MM-DD)
	-I, --inactive INACTIVE â†’ Set inactive days post expiry
	-m, --mindays MIN_DAYS â†’ Minimum password age (days before change)
	-M, --maxdays MAX_DAYS â†’ Maximum password age (password expiry)
	-W, --warndays WARN_DAYS â†’ Expiry warning days
	-i, --iso8601 â†’ Use ISO 8601 date output
	-h, --help â†’ Display help message

Switching Users
	su username â†’ Switch user without loading environment
	su - username â†’ Full login shell for user
	sudo -i	-> Full login shell for root
	sudo -s	-> Shell for root without loading environment

Permission Commands
	chown username file/foldername â†’ Change file owner
	chown -R username foldername â†’ Recursively change ownership
	chgrp groupname file/foldername â†’ Change group
	chgrp -R groupname foldername â†’ Recursively change group
	chown username:groupname file/foldername â†’ Change user & group
	chmod 777 file/foldername â†’ Change permissions

	chmod 2775 shared_dir : New files inside the directory inherit the directory's group

    Very important command :    
	sudo chattr +i filename -> a file is marked as immutable, it cannot be modified, deleted, or renamed, even by the root user
    lsattr filename -> To check the attributes of a file
    chattr +a filename -> Append-only attribute, only allows appending data
	sudo chattr -i filename -> To remove the immutable attribute
	lsattr filename ->  To check the attributes of a file

	The umask (user file creation mask) command controls the default file permissions assigned when a file or directory is created. 
	The value of umask acts as a subtractive mask, which subtracts permissions from the default 666 (for files) or 777 (for directories).
	umask 022 â†’ Default permissions for files: 644, directories: 755
	umask 027 â†’ Default permissions for files: 640, directories: 750
	set umask 027 â†’ Set umask for the current session
	
	ufw means Uncomplicated Firewall

	ufw status verbose â†’ Show firewall status
	ufw allow 22/tcp â†’ Allow SSH traffic
	ufw allow 80/tcp â†’ Allow HTTP traffic
	ufw allow 443/tcp â†’ Allow HTTPS traffic
	ufw deny 22/tcp â†’ Deny Telnet traffic

	sudo ufw status numbered â†’ Show numbered rules
	sudo ufw delete 6   # delete the rule with higher number first
	sudo ufw delete 5   # then delete the one that was above it

	namei -l /path/to/file.txt  # Shows permissions at each level
	namei -m /path/to/file.txt  # Shows permissions and ownership at each level

ps -aux | grep processname 
--> It shows all processes running on the system, including those owned by other users.
a --> Show processes for all users
u --> Show user-oriented format
x --> Show processes that don't have controlling terminal (Eg: daemon processes, background processes)	

ps -ef --sort=%cpu   # Sort processes by CPU usage (ascending)
ps -ef --sort=-%cpu   # Sort processes by CPU usage (descending)
ps -ef --sort=-%mem   # Sort processes by memory usage (descending)

ps -ef | grep processname  <--> ps -fp PID
--> It shows all processes running on the system, including those owned by other users.
-e --> Show all processes
-f --> Show full format listing (including command line arguments, PPID)
	
pkill [options] pattern
Common Flags:
Flag	Description
-f	Match the full command line instead of just the process name
-e	Echo the names of the processes killed
-n	Target the newest matching process
-o	Target the oldest matching process
-u  USER	Kill processes owned by the specified user
-x	Match the exact process name (not substring)
-l	List the process names instead of killing them
-signal	Send a specific signal (e.g., -9 for SIGKILL, -HUP, -SIGTERM)
Examples:
	pkill firefox â†’ Kills all processes named "firefox"
	pkill -l firefox â†’ Lists all processes named "firefox" without killing them
	pkill -f python â†’ Kills any process with "python" in its full command line
	pkill -9 nginx â†’ Forcefully kills nginx processes
	pkill -u bob â†’ Kills all processes owned by user "bob" 
	pkill -o python â†’ Kills the oldest python process
	pkill -n vim â†’ Kills the most recent vim process
	pkill -x sshd â†’ Kills only if the process name is exactly "sshd"
	pkill -e python â†’ Echo the names of processes being killed

pgrep [options] pattern --> It prints the process IDs (PIDs) of running processes that match the given name or pattern.
Common Flags:	
Option | Description | Example
-l | Show PID and process name | pgrep -l python
-u <user> | Show processes for a specific user | pgrep -u peeyush
-f | Match full command line, not just name | pgrep -f myscript.py
-n | Return only the newest matching process | pgrep -n python
-o | Return only the oldest matching process | pgrep -o python
-v | Invert match (exclude matches) | pgrep -v bash
-d <char> | Set delimiter for PIDs (default newline) | pgrep -d, python â†’ 1234,1240

Signal	Number	Name	Description
  0	    0	    N/A	    Check if a process exists (no signal sent). 0 â†’ Process exists, and you can signal it
SIGHUP	1	  Hangup	Reload config or indicate terminal disconnect
SIGINT	2	 Interrupt	Sent by Ctrl+C to interrupt a process
SIGQUIT	3	   Quit   	Sent by Ctrl+\, creates a core dump
SIGILL	4	 Illegal	Illegal instruction (invalid machine code)
SIGABRT	6	  Abort	    Sent by process to abort (e.g., via abort() call)
SIGFPE	7	   FPE	    Floating-point exception (e.g., division by zero)
SIGKILL	9	   Kill	    Forces immediate process termination; cannot be caught or ignored
SIGSEGV	11	 Segfault	Invalid memory access (segmentation fault)
SIGPIPE	13	  Broken	Pipe broken (e.g., writing to closed pipe)
SIGALRM	14	  Alarm		Timer signal from alarm()
SIGTERM	15	 Terminate	Graceful termination (can be caught or ignored by process)
SIGCONT	18	 Continue	Resume a stopped process
SIGSTOP	19	  Stop	    Pause process (canâ€™t be caught or ignored)
SIGTSTP	20	  TSTP	   	Terminal Stop process (sent by Ctrl+Z)

kill -l â†’ List all signals
kill -l 1 â†’ List signal number 1 (SIGHUP)
kill -l SIGINT â†’ List signal name (SIGINT)
kill -15 <PID>        # Graceful stop using SIGTERM
kill -9 <PID>         # Force kill using SIGKILL
kill -1 <PID>         # Reload config (SIGHUP)
kill -18 <PID>        # Continue a stopped process (SIGCONT)
kill -19 <PID>        # Stop (pause) a process (SIGSTOP)

pkill -SIGTERM firefox   # Gracefully stop firefox
pkill -9 apache2         # Force kill apache2 processes

Ignores hangup signal
Keeps processes running after terminal logout

You're an IT admin connecting to a remote Linux server over SSH. You're about to leave for the airport, but you need to start a long-running
backup of important files to another server. You wonâ€™t be connected to the terminal after your laptop goes to sleep or disconnects from Wi-Fi.

screen -S mysession
rsync -avz -e "ssh -i ~/.ssh/id_ed25519" file.txt user@remote:/path/
# Press Ctrl+A, then D to detach from the screen session
# Press Ctrl+A, then K to kill the screen session
# To reattach later, use:
screen -r mysession --> Reattach to the screen session
screen -XS backupjob quit --> Terminate the screen session
screen -ls --> List all screen sessions

screen -dmS mysession bash -c 'rsync -avz /var/www/ user@backupserver:/backups/; exec bash' 
-d â†’ Start detached (donâ€™t attach to it)
-m â†’ Force screen to create a new session
-S â†’ Name the screen session

We can add this in crontab :
0 1 * * * /usr/bin/screen -dmS nightlybackup bash -c 'rsync -avz /var/www/ user@backupserver:/backups/ > /var/log/nightlybackup.log 2>&1; exec bash'


nohup rsync -avz /var/www/ user@backupserver:/backups/ > backup.log 2>&1 &
nohup â†’ ignores hangup signal (keeps running after logout)
> backup.log 2>&1 â†’ saves both stdout and stderr to a log file
& â†’ runs in background so you can close the terminal

cd /home/user/projects
nohup python script.py &  # Creates /home/user/projects/nohup.out 

Network Commands
1)ping -c 5 -i 0.2 -W 1 app-server.internal --> 5 packets, interval of 0.2 seconds, timeout of 1 second
2)mtr -rwzbc 50 google.com
This command runs mtr (My Traceroute) in report mode to analyze the network path from your machine to google.com, sending 50 packets, skipping DNS resolution, and printing a clean, wide-formatted, easy-to-read report.
Flag	Meaning
-r	Report mode â€“ useful for logging or automation
-w	Wide output â€“ full IPs and hostnames, no truncation
-z	Show latency jitter (useful for spotting network instability)
-b	Show both IP address and hostname
-c 50	Send 50 pings per hop to get a reliable average
	
3)traceroute -n -p 443 api.example.com	--> Traces the route to api.example.com using port 443
Flag	                   Description 
-n	                       No DNS lookup â€“ shows IPs only (faster, avoids DNS delays)
-p 443	                   Target port 443 â€“ used to mimic actual HTTPS traffic (can help bypass firewalls)
api.example.com	           Destination â€“ resolved to an IP and probed hop by hop

4)
â€¢ wget: Primarily used for downloading files over HTTP, HTTPS, and FTP. It's designed to fetch content from the web, often used for bulk downloads or mirroring websites.
â€¢ curl: A tool for transferring data to or from a server, supporting multiple protocols (HTTP, HTTPS, FTP, SFTP, SCP, and more). 
        It's more flexible and can handle various data transfer tasks beyond just downloading files.

wget -r -l2 -nc --limit-rate=500k --user-agent="Mozilla/5.0" --no-check-certificate -P -N 
/path/to/save https://example.com

Explanation:-
	â€¢ -r: Recursively download the website.`
	â€¢ -l2: Limit the recursion depth to 2 levels (you can increase or decrease as needed).
	â€¢ -nc: Skip downloading files that already exist (no clobber).
	â€¢ --limit-rate=500k: Limit download speed to 500 KB/s.
	â€¢ --user-agent or -U ="Mozilla/5.0": Set a custom user-agent (useful for websites blocking default agents).
	â€¢ --no-check-certificate: Ignore SSL certificate verification (use with caution).
	â€¢ -P /path/to/save: Save the files to a specific directory (replace with your desired path).
	â€¢ https://example.com: The URL of the website you want to download.
	â€¢ -N To download only files that have been modified since your last download
	â€¢ -b --> download in the background, so you can continue using the terminal.
	â€¢ -c --> download was interrupted, you can resume it with the -c flag.
	â€¢ wget -i urls.txt --> You can download a list of files by providing a text file with the URLs.
	â€¢ wget -O myfile.zip https://example.com/file.zip  --> rename the file after downloading
	â€¢ wget -q --show-progress https://example.com/file.zip --> quiet mode with progress bar
	â€¢ wget -m https://example.com/file.zip -->Mirror, Downloads all of the website's content recursively, including directories, 
											subdirectories, and linked pages, while preserving the original directory structure.
	  wget --tries=inf http://download.virtualbox.org/virtualbox/rpm/rhel/virtualbox.repo

For practice go through this website : https://phoenixnap.com/kb/wget-command-with-examples	

