curl -O --limit-rate 500k -A -z "Mozilla/5.0" -k https://example.com/file.zip:
â€¢ -O: Save the file with the same name as on the server.
  -o newname.zip: Save the file with a custom name.
â€¢ --limit-rate 500k: Limits the download speed to 500 KB/s.
â€¢ -# : Show progress bar.
â€¢ -A "Mozilla/5.0": Sets the custom user-agent (mimicking a browser).
â€¢ -k: Ignores SSL certificate verification.
â€¢ -z: If you want to download the file only if itâ€™s newer, you can use the -z 
â€¢ curl -C - -O https://example.com/largefile.zip --> Supports resuming downloads with the -C - flag
â€¢ curl -o newname.zip https://example.com/file.zip
â€¢ --retry 3: Retry the download 3 times in case of failure.
â€¢ --timeout 30: Set the connection timeout to 30 seconds.
â€¢ -L: Follow redirects (in case the URL redirects to another location).
â€¢ -w "%{http_code}\n": Print the HTTP response code (e.g., 200 for success, 404 for not found).
â€¢ -s: Silent mode (no progress bar or error messages).
â€¢ -z: Download the file only if it has been modified since the last download.
â€¢ -K urls.txt: Download multiple files from a list in urls.txt. Eg: url = "https://example.com/file1.zip" in urls.txt
â€¢ --form "file=@/path/to/file" https://example.com/upload: Upload a file using a form submission.
â€¢ -u username:password URL : Use basic authentication with the provided username and password.
â€¢ -T 30: Set the connection timeout to 30 seconds.
â€¢ --data "username=user&password=pass": Send data with the request (e.g., for form submissions).	

Feature                      | wget Flag              | curl Flag      	     | Description
Download file with same name | Default         		  | -O             	     | Saves with original name in wget; curl needs -O.
Download with custom name 	 | -O newname.zip  		  | -o newname.zip 	     | Rename file after download.
Recursive download           | -r                     | âŒ             	   | Only wget supports recursion.
Recursion depth 			 | -l2 			          | âŒ 			  	   | Only in wget; sets max recursion level.
Skip existing files 		 | -nc 			          | âŒ 			       | wget's --no-clobber skips existing files.
Limit download speed 		 |--limit-rate=500k       | --limit-rate 500k    | Both support speed limiting.
Set user-agent 				 | --user-agent="..." or -U | -A "..."           | Mimics browser user-agent.
Ignore SSL cert check        | --no-check-certificate | -k                   | Disables SSL verification.
Save to specific directory   | -P /path/              | -o /path/filename    | wget saves to dir; curl needs full output path.
Download if updated			 | -N 					  | -z filename 	     | Downloads only if newer than local file.
Background download 		 | -b 					  | âŒ 				   | Only wget supports background mode.
Resume broken download 		 | -c 					  | -C - 				 | Both support resuming partial downloads.
Download from list 			 | -i urls.txt 			  | -K urls.txt 		 | wget supports URL lists from file.
Quiet with progress bar 	 | -q --show-progress 	  | -s 					 | Both support silent mode with some output.
Mirror entire site           | -m 					  | âŒ 				   | Only wget can mirror sites recursively.
Infinite retry 			     | --tries=inf 			  | --retry 3            | wget can retry forever; curl needs manual retry count.
Set timeout 				 | --timeout=30 		  | --max-time 30 		 | Both support setting timeouts.
Follow redirects 			 | Default 				  | -L 					 | wget follows redirects by default; curl needs -L.
Print HTTP status code 		 | âŒ 				     | -w "%{http_code}\n" | Only curl can print HTTP status directly.

