rsync -avhz --delete-after --exclude 'logs/' --bwlimit=1000 --backup --backup-dir=/backup-old -e "ssh -p 2222" /data/ user@server:/backup/
â€¢ -a: Archive mode
â€¢ -v: Verbose
â€¢ -z: Compress during transfer
â€¢ --delete: Delete remote files that are not in the source (if youâ€™re unsure! Use --dry-run to preview)
  --delete-before: Deletes files on the destination before transferring new ones
  --delete-after: Deletes files on the destination after transferring new ones 
  	(Safer; ensures files are not deleted until the transfer is completed)
â€¢ --exclude 'logs/': Exclude logs directory
â€¢ --bwlimit=1000: Limit bandwidth to 1000 KB/s
â€¢ --backup: Backup overwritten files
â€¢ --backup-dir=/backup-old: Directory for backups of overwritten files
â€¢ -e "ssh -p 2222": Use SSH on port 2222
â€¢ -h: Human-readable: makes file sizes easier to read (e.g., 10M, 1G)
â€¢ --suffix=.bak: Append .bak to the backup file

â€¢ rsync -avz --dry-run /data/ user@server:/backup/
--dry-run : hows what files would be transferred, but doesnâ€™t actually do it.

â€¢ rsync -avz --progress /data/ user@server:/backup/
--progress: Shows progress during transfer

â€¢ rsync -avz --remove-source-files /data/ user@server:/backup/      
--remove-source-files: Deletes source files after transfer

â€¢ rsync -avz --ignore-existing /data/ user@server:/backup/
--ignore-existing: Skips files that already exist on the destination means 
  it will not overwrite existing files on the destination

â€¢ rsync -avz --update /data/ user@server:/backup/
--update: Source file is newer than destination file (based on timestamp)

â€¢ rsync -avz --checksum /data/ user@server:/backup/
--checksum: Compares files based on checksum instead of timestamp . Copy only if the checksum is different
  (slower, but ensures files are identical)

â€¢ rsync -avz --exclude-from='exclude.txt' /data/ user@server:/backup/
--exclude-from: Excludes files listed in exclude.txt        

â€¢ rsync -avz --include='*.txt' --exclude='*' /data/ user@server:/backup/
--include: Includes only .txt files, excludes everything else

â€¢ rsync -av --prune-empty-dirs /source/ user@server:/backup/
--prune-empty-dirs: Removes empty directories from the transfer

â€¢ rsync --partial --append -avz file.iso user@remote:/data/
--partial: Keeps partially transferred files
--append: Appends data to partially transferred files
  Assumes the partial file is intact. Risky if corruption occurred during interruption.

â€¢ rsync --partial --append-verify -avz file.iso user@remote:/data/
,--append-verify: Appends data to partially transferred files and verifies the integrity of the transferred data
  Compares hashes of existing data before resuming. Safer for backups and critical files.


scp -P -C 2222 -r -i /path/to/key.pem/data/ user@server:/backup/
â€¢ -C: Compress data during transfer
â€¢ -P: Use port 2222
â€¢ -r: Recursively copy directories
â€¢ -i: Use the specified private key for authentication
â€¢ -v: Verbose output
â€¢ -q: Quiet mode, suppresses progress and error messages
â€¢ -p: Preserves file attributes (timestamps, permissions)
â€¢ -l: Limits the bandwidth used (e.g., 1000k for 1000 KB/s) Eg: scp -l 1000   

